  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Identifying and verifying customer information\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Ongoing monitoring of customer activities\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n5. Legal Penalties\n- Potential significant fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced by laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and regulated by agencies such as FinCEN in the United States.\n\nSpecific requirements can vary by jurisdiction, but most developed countries have robust legal frameworks to combat money laundering in the financial sector.",
